{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e855d3b3-2038-4e1d-9e08-86d2ddde9fe0","content":"Your tutorial's advice is **partially correct** but has a nuance worth knowing:\n\n### ✅ `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` — Correct\n\nThis is the standard .NET MAUI approach and still applies in .NET 10. Make sure you have the right namespace:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\nThis automatically adds padding so content avoids the notch/Dynamic Island and home indicator.\n\n### ⚠️ `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` — Not a standard MAUI property\n\nThere is **no built-in `IgnoreSafeArea`** property on `Grid` or other layouts in .NET MAUI. The tutorial may be referencing a third-party library or outdated/incorrect information.\n\n**To let a background image extend behind the notch** while keeping other content safe, structure your layout like this:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"...\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n    <Grid>\n        <!-- Background spans full screen (behind notch) -->\n        <Image Source=\"bg.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n\n        <!-- Content respects safe area via manual padding -->\n        <Grid Padding=\"{OnPlatform iOS='47,0,34,0'}\">\n            <!-- Your actual content here -->\n        </Grid>\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nOr better, set `UseSafeArea=\"True\"` on the page and use negative margins on the background image to extend it beyond the safe area. The key idea: **page-level** `UseSafeArea` controls padding; there's no per-view opt-out built in.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"24707155-c13d-416f-aa79-f7cf7307167d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - for handling iPhone notch\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - on a Grid for background images\n\nLet me check what I know about .NET MAUI safe area APIs, particularly for .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the safe area handling for iOS has evolved:\n\n- In earlier versions (Xamarin.Forms), `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` was the platform-specific way to handle safe areas on iOS.\n\n\n- In .NET MAUI, the equivalent is `Page.SetUseSafeArea(true)` or in XAML it's still accessible via platform specifics, though the namespace changed from Xamarin.Forms to Microsoft.Maui.\n- For `IgnoreSafeArea`, .NET MAUI provides a way to set this on views to allow content to extend into the safe area, which is useful for background images that should span the full screen.\n- These APIs should remain valid in .NET 10, so the migration path from Xamarin.Forms is fairly straightforward—mostly just updating namespaces and method names. I'm second-guessing myself on the exact implementation details here. In .NET MAUI, `UseSafeArea` on the Page is definitely the right approach, but for individual views that need to extend beyond the safe area—like background elements—I'd likely need to use negative margins or padding adjustments rather than a direct `IgnoreSafeArea` property. margins or handle it programmatically.\n\nI'm not entirely sure about `IgnoreSafeArea` as a standard .NET MAUI property—it might be outdated or specific to certain versions. The reliable approach in .NET MAUI is using `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` to handle safe area padding automatically, or structuring your layout so background elements sit at the page level while content respects the safe area constraints. I'll go with what I'm confident about and clarify the `IgnoreSafeArea` situation in my response.","outputTokens":1610},"id":"ed818ce0-920d-483c-80e7-5d0466301861","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:55:07.642Z","parentId":"f5cc50b4-8de9-49c9-9c74-575a29d7cf72"}
